{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Agree Option B with reservation: keep brief Poetic/Non-Rational mention",
    "content": "Agree with Option B, with one reservation.\n\nMoving the full terminological apparatus to a glossary introduction is the right call — the Preface should be a narrative that prepares the reader experientially for the collection, not a reference document. Readers will consult terminology when they encounter it, not before.\n\nMy reservation: \"The Poetic\" and \"The Non-Rational\" are not merely terminological entries — they are conceptual orientations that shape how the reader approaches the entire collection. If the reader encounters \"the Poetic\" for the first time in Essay 5 or 6 without any preparation, they may read it as an aesthetic category rather than an existential stance. I'd suggest keeping a single bridging paragraph in the Preface (3-4 sentences, not the full subsections) that names these two concepts and signals their importance — something like: \"Two concepts deserve advance mention: the Poetic (诗意), the author's central positive proposal for how to inhabit meaning-structures lucidly; and the non-rational (非理性), the acknowledged ground beneath all rational activity. These are developed in Part 2 and discussed fully in the glossary.\" Everything else — Constancy, Dreamscape, Vain Presumption, the Dao-De-Ren-Yi-Li sequence, Three Realities — can move to the glossary introduction without loss.\n\nAgree on both smaller trims. The working-draft paragraph is redundant. The forward references to \"digestion\" and \"knowledge sub-category\" are confusing at that point in reading."
  }
}
